## 2.  The **Three Core Problems** Thiel would flag

| Problem | Why it would make Thiel raise an eyebrow | Why it matters to his worldview |
|---|---|---|
| **Over‑centralised governance** (Global Council, Regional Assemblies, RRC) | Thiel’s *flat‑hierarchy* mantra (“the flatter the organization, the faster the innovation”) is the opposite of a three‑tiered bureaucracy. He sees the *pyramid* as a *drag on decision‑making speed*. | If the charter obliges **all major decisions** to pass through multiple layers of citizen‑assemblies, one‑by‑one voting, and multi‑year consensus cycles, **innovation cycles** (which need weeks, not years) will be throttled, making it impossible to launch breakthrough technologies quickly enough to stay ahead of competitors. |
| **The Common‑Future Fund (CFF) as a redistributive, centrally‑planned pool** | Thiel’s hallmark is *“creative monopoly”* funded by *private capital*, not by forced redistribution. A centrally‑planned fund that must *redistribute* a share of global GDP *by force* is anathemic to his *“creative capitalism”* philosophy. | A monopoly (or monopoly‑like power over a resource) is, in his view, *acceptable only when it is created by a genuinely better product*; a redistributive fund financed by progressive taxes is **redistribution**, not innovation. |
| **Concentration‑Threshold Rule & Antitrust Enforcement** | Thiel’s approach to antitrust is *highly selective*: he believes *some* monopolies are *necessary* (e.g., Google, Facebook) because they fund massive R&D. He would balk at a rule that *forces divestiture* or *breaks up monopolies* simply because they are “too big.” | In his view, *forcing monopolies to break up* just for the sake of competition removes the *economies of scale* that enable massive cost reductions and technology breakthroughs (e.g., the shift from batch processing to cloud compute). |
| **Algorithmic Ethics Board with mandatory explainability requirements** | Thiel’s “algorithmic ethics” is *not a regulatory burden* but a *strategic advantage*: the best AI systems are those that can *show why they make a decision* (because it helps with safety, not compliance). | However, he would argue that binding *explainability* requirements for *all* AI models, even those that are purely internal utilities, is an *over‑reach* that will **slow down AI development** and make it prohibitively expensive to build next‑gen models. He would rather *let the market decide* the level of explainability needed for each niche. |
| **Universal Carbon‑Pricing / “Triple‑Bottom‑Line” Test** | Thiel is skeptical of *“pricing carbon”* as a blanket solution; he believes that **pricing externalities** works *only when markets can actually price them*—i.e., when they are *liquid* and *liquidizable* (e.g., futures on carbon credits). A globally‑applied cap‑and‑trade scheme without *clear price signals* will be **inefficient** and easily gamed. | Thiel’s view is that **market mechanisms must be left to discover the true price of carbon** without a globally‑imposed ceiling; otherwise you end up with *price controls that cripple investment* in the very technologies that could solve the problem (e.g., next‑gen nuclear, high‑altitude wind turbines). |

**Bottom line:** Thiel’s critique boils down to: *“Your charter tries to solve the world’s problems by imposing centrally‑planned constraints, while the real driver of breakthrough progress is competition, private property, and *unrestricted* innovation.”*

